{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528720","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528720"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:46:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:46:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14325"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14325","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14325"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.54,0.21,0.03,0.18,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7020"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54609"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7020","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7020"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14325"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40126"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1074"},{"type":"tags","id":"1881"},{"type":"tags","id":"2355"},{"type":"tags","id":"2697"},{"type":"tags","id":"4020"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4978"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11624"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16687"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41947"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54609","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54609"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with symptoms of opioid withdrawal. She reports using heroin daily for the past three years and last used 12 hours ago. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears distressed with a pulse rate of 100/min, blood pressure 140/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. She is diaphoretic, has mild tremors, and complains of nausea and abdominal cramps. Her pupils are dilated to 5 mm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Clinical Opiate Withdrawal Scale (COWS) score is calculated to be 14, indicating moderate withdrawal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Start buprenorphine sublingually","Initiate methadone orally","Administer morphine intravenously","Begin naltrexone orally","Prescribe clonidine orally"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this scenario, the most appropriate next step in management is to \u003Cstrong\u003Estart buprenorphine sublingually\u003C/strong\u003E. Buprenorphine is considered the first-line treatment for opioid replacement therapy due to its favorable safety profile and effectiveness in managing opioid withdrawal symptoms and cravings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInitiating methadone\u003C/strong\u003E is an alternative option for opioid replacement therapy. However, buprenorphine is generally preferred as the first-line treatment due to its better safety profile, lower risk of respiratory depression, and easier dosing regimen. Methadone also has a higher risk of overdose, especially in opioid-naive individuals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering morphine\u003C/strong\u003E intravenously would not be appropriate as it perpetuates the cycle of opioid dependence and does not address the underlying addiction. The goal is to transition the patient to a safer, long-acting opioid replacement therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrescribing clonidine\u003C/strong\u003E can be helpful for managing some withdrawal symptoms, such as anxiety and autonomic symptoms. However, it is not a replacement therapy and would not be the most appropriate first-line treatment in this situation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeginning naltrexone\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in a patient actively using opioids or in acute withdrawal. Naltrexone is an opioid antagonist used for relapse prevention in patients who have already completed detoxification. Administering naltrexone to this patient would precipitate severe withdrawal symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to initiating buprenorphine is timing. It should be started when the patient is in mild to moderate withdrawal (typically COWS score \u22658) to avoid precipitated withdrawal. In this case, the patient\u0027s COWS score of 14 indicates moderate withdrawal, making it an appropriate time to initiate buprenorphine. The initial dose can be repeated after 1-2 hours if withdrawal symptoms persist, with subsequent doses adjusted based on the patient\u0027s response.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter initiating buprenorphine, the patient should be monitored for symptom improvement and potential side effects. The goal is to stabilize the patient and transition them to ongoing addiction treatment and support services.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Buprenorphine is the preferred first-line treatment for opioid replacement therapy due to its safety profile and effectiveness.","Initiation of buprenorphine should occur when the patient is in mild to moderate withdrawal to avoid precipitated withdrawal.","The Clinical Opiate Withdrawal Scale (COWS) is a useful tool for assessing the severity of opioid withdrawal symptoms."],"references":["Frei M. Opioid dependence-management in general practice. Australian family physician. 2010 Aug;39(8):548-52."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40126"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14325"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40126","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40126"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-08T08:46:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-08T08:47:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7020"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54609"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/43"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc8a","name":"Pharmacology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":